  "15-28": (
    caption: [Glycogen breakdown near an ((cid:2)1n6) branch point. Following sequential removal of terminal glucose residues by glycogen phosphorylase (see Fig. 15–27), glucose residues near a branch are removed in a two-step process that requires a bifunctional debranching enzyme. First, the transferase activity of the enzyme shifts a block of three glucose residues from the branch to a nearby nonreducing end, to which they are reattached in ((cid:7)1n4) linkage. The single glucose residue remaining at the branch point, in ((cid:7)1n6) linkage, is then released as free glucose by the debranching enzyme's ((cid:7)1n6) glucosidase activity. The glucose residues are shown in shorthand form, which omits the OH, OOH, and OCH2OH groups from the pyranose rings.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
